# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elasticsearch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Lucene has been ported to other programming languages including Object Pascal, Perl, C#, C++, Python, Ruby and PHP.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Doug Cutting originally wrote Lucene in 1999.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] He had previously written two while at Xerox PARC, one at Apple, and a fourth at Excite.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] It was initially available for download from its home at the SourceForge web site.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] It joined the Apache Software Foundation's Jakarta family of open-source Java products in September 2001 and became its own top-level Apache project in February 2005.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] The name Lucene is Doug Cutting's wife's middle name and her maternal grandmother's first name.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Lucene formerly included a number of sub-projects, such as Lucene.NET, Mahout, Tika and Nutch.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] These three are now independent top-level projects.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] In March 2010, the Apache Solr search server joined as a Lucene sub-project, merging the developer communities.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Version 4.0 was released on October 12, 2012.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] In March 2021, Lucene changed its logo, and Apache Solr became a top level Apache project again, independent from Lucene.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] While suitable for any application that requires full text indexing and searching capability, Lucene is recognized for its utility in the implementation of Internet search engines and local, single-site searching.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Lucene includes a feature to perform a fuzzy search based on edit distance.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Lucene has also been used to implement recommendation systems.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] For example, Lucene's 'MoreLikeThis' Class can generate recommendations for similar documents.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] In contrast, citation-based document similarity measures tended to be more suitable for recommending more broadly related documents, meaning citation-based approaches may be more suitable for generating serendipitous recommendations, as long as documents to be recommended contain in-text citations.
[src:elasticsearch/apache-lucene] Lucene itself is just an indexing and search library and does not contain crawling and HTML parsing functionality.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] An *index* is the fundamental unit of storage in Elasticsearch, and the level at which you interact with your data.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] You can store many independent datasets side by side.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] To store a document, you add it to a specific index.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] To search, you target one or more indices.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Elasticsearch searches all data within them and returns any matching documents.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] You can target your data by index name, through an alias that points to one or more indices, or through a data stream that routes requests to the appropriate backing indices.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Behind the scenes, Elasticsearch divides each index into *shards* and distributes them across the nodes in your cluster.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] The horizontal scaling of your *primary* shard into *replica* shards across other nodes allows your index to handle large volumes of traffic efficiently.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Replica shards provide fault tolerance, keeping your data available even when an individual node's response fails.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] This page explains the core parts of an index (*documents*, *mappings*, and *settings*), describes how Elasticsearch physically stores index data using *shards*, and highlights common design decisions.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Elasticsearch serializes and stores data in the form of JSON documents.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] A document is a set of fields, which are key-value pairs that contain your data.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Each document has a unique ID, which you can specify explicitly or have Elasticsearch auto-generate.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] An indexed document includes both document fields you define and system-managed metadata.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] The `_source` field contains the original document body as submitted.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] The fields inside `_source` are the ones you control through mappings.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] You can define these mappings explicitly or have Elasticsearch create them for you dynamically when your data is ingested.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Each index has a mapping that defines the data type for each field, how the field should be indexed, and how it should be stored.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Each index has settings that control its storage and performance behavior.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Settings are configured when the index is created, either directly in the create index request or through an index template.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Some index settings can be updated dynamically on a live index.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] For the full list of available settings, refer to Index settings.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] When you create an index, Elasticsearch doesn't store all its documents in a single location.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Instead, it divides the index into one or more *shards* and distributes those shards across the nodes in your cluster.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Each shard is a self-contained Apache Lucene index with practical limits on how much data it can efficiently manage, so splitting data across multiple shards keeps individual shards performant.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Distributing those shards across cluster nodes adds horizontal scaling and redundancy.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] The right number of shards depends on your data volume, query patterns, and cluster topology — there is no single correct answer.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Refer to shard sizing and distribution recommendations for more information and best practices.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] You don't interact with shards directly when indexing or searching.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Instead, you target the index by name and Elasticsearch routes the operation to the appropriate shards.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] However, the number and size of shards you configure affects performance and stability.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Refer to Common index design decisions for more information.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] A shard holds a subset of the index's documents and can independently handle indexing and search operations.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] Inside each shard, data is organized into immutable *segments* that are written as documents are indexed.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] To learn how segments affect search availability, refer to Near real-time search.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] By distributing shards across multiple nodes, Elasticsearch can scale horizontally and continue operating even when individual nodes fail.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] For a detailed explanation of this distributed model, refer to Distributed architecture.
[src:elasticsearch/documents-indices] To learn how Elasticsearch coordinates reads and writes across primary and replica shards, refer to Reading and writing documents.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:elasticsearch/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] In text retrieval, **full-text search** refers to a set of techniques for searching a single computer-stored document or a collection in a full-text database.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Full-text search is distinguished from searches based on metadata or on specific parts of documents, such as titles, abstracts, selected sections, or bibliographical references.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] In a full-text search, a search engine examines the words in stored documents to find matches for user queries.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Full-text-search techniques began to appear in the 1960s (for example, IBM STAIRS in 1969), and became common in online bibliographic databases during the 1990s.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Many websites and application programs, including word processors, implement full-text search functionality.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Some web search engines, such as the former AltaVista, indexed the full text of web pages, while others indexed only selected portions of pages.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] When dealing with a small number of documents, a full-text-search engine can scan the contents of each document directly for every query, a strategy known as "serial scanning." Some tools, such as grep, operate in this way.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] When the number of documents or queries is large, full-text search is typically divided into two tasks: indexing and searching.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] During indexing, the engine scans all documents and builds a list of search terms, often called an index, or more precisely, a concordance.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] During the search stage, queries are performed against the index rather than the original documents.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The indexer records each term found in a document and may note its position within the text.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Common words, known as stop words (for instance, "the" or "and"), are omitted because they add little value to search results.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The diagram at the right illustrates a search with low recall and low precision.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] In the diagram, red and green dots represent the total population of potential search results for a given query, with green dots indicating relevant results and red indicating irrelevant results.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Relevance is indicated by proximity to the center of the inner circle.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The results actually returned by the search are highlighted on a light-blue background.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] In the example, only one relevant result of three possible relevant results was returned, giving a recall of ⅓ (33%).
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The precision is 1/4 (25%), since only one of the four results returned was relevant.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Due to the ambiguities of natural language, full-text-search systems typically include features such as filtering to increase precision and stemming to increase recall.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Controlled-vocabulary search can also help alleviate low-precision results by tagging documents to reduce ambiguity.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] There is generally a trade-off between precision and recall: increasing precision can reduce overall recall, while increasing recall may lower precision.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Full-text search can retrieve many documents that are not relevant to the intended query.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Such documents are called **false positives** (see Type I error).
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The retrieval of irrelevant documents is often caused by the inherent ambiguity of natural language.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] In the accompanying diagram, false positives are represented by irrelevant results (red dots) that were returned by the search (highlighted on a light-blue background).
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] At a basic level, search engines return items that contain the exact phrase listed in the query.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Tools and methodologies exist to account for grammatical or typographical errors and to refine results; however, these techniques still typically require a close textual match.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Because there are often multiple ways to refer to an entity or concept, full-text search may fail to retrieve an item if the exact term is not used in the query.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Not to be confused with semantic search, synonyms can be retrieved by creating an index of related terms, such that when a variation of a word is searched, items containing any of the related terms may also be returned.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The limitations of full-text searching have been addressed in two ways: by providing users with tools to express search questions more precisely, and by developing algorithms that improve retrieval precision.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] The following is a partial list of software products that support full-text indexing and search.
[src:elasticsearch/full-text-search] Some of these are accompanied by documentation describing their architecture or algorithms, which may provide additional insight into how full-text search is implemented.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The purpose of an inverted index is to allow fast full-text searches, at a cost of increased processing when a document is added to the database.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The inverted file may be the database file itself, rather than its index.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] It is the most popular data structure used in document retrieval systems, used on a large scale for example in search engines.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] Additionally, several significant general-purpose mainframe-based database management systems have used inverted list architectures, including ADABAS, DATACOM/DB, and Model 204.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] There are two main variants of inverted indexes: A **record-level inverted index** (or **inverted file index** or just **inverted file**) contains a list of references to documents for each word.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] A **word-level inverted index** (or **full inverted index** or **inverted list**) additionally contains the positions of each word within a document.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The latter form offers more functionality (like phrase searches), but needs more processing power and space to be created.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The inverted index data structure is a central component of a typical search engine indexing algorithm.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] A goal of a search engine implementation is to optimize the speed of the query: find the documents where word X occurs.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] Once a forward index is developed, which stores lists of words per document, it is next inverted to develop an inverted index.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] Querying the forward index would require sequential iteration through each document and to each word to verify a matching document.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The time, memory, and processing resources to perform such a query are not always technically realistic.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] Instead of listing the words per document in the forward index, the inverted index data structure is developed which lists the documents per word.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] With the inverted index created, the query can be resolved by jumping to the word ID (via random access) in the inverted index.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] In pre-computer times, concordances to important books were manually assembled.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] These were effectively inverted indexes with a small amount of accompanying commentary that required a tremendous amount of effort to produce.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] In bioinformatics, inverted indexes are very important in the sequence assembly of short fragments of sequenced DNA.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] One way to find the source of a fragment is to search for it against a reference DNA sequence.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] A small number of mismatches (due to differences between the sequenced DNA and reference DNA, or errors) can be accounted for by dividing the fragment into smaller fragments—at least one subfragment is likely to match the reference DNA sequence.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] The matching requires constructing an inverted index of all substrings of a certain length from the reference DNA sequence.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] Since the human DNA contains more than 3 billion base pairs, and we need to store a DNA substring for every index and a 32-bit integer for index itself, the storage requirement for such an inverted index would probably be in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:elasticsearch/inverted-index] For historical reasons, inverted list compression and bitmap compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:elasticsearch/reference-index] Elasticsearch is a distributed search and analytics engine, scalable data store, and vector database built on Apache Lucene.
[src:elasticsearch/reference-index] It’s optimized for speed and relevance on production-scale workloads.
[src:elasticsearch/reference-index] Use Elasticsearch to search, index, store, and analyze data of all shapes and sizes in near real time.
[src:elasticsearch/reference-index] Elasticsearch is the search and analytics engine that powers the Elastic Stack.
